<h1><%= title_for(IdeatorLesson, 3, 4) %></h1>

<p>
  Now that we've got a navbar going on, let's add a footer. What we want is a footer that sticks to the bottom of the screen no matter how much content you have. Sometimes when a website has no content, the footer will float above the bottom of the screen. What we want is a <i>sticky</i> footer. We're going to try and find a template that we can use to implement this sticky footer.
</p>

<p>
  If we run a google search for "bootstrap sticky footer", we can find a StackOverflow post that talks this issue <a href = "http://stackoverflow.com/a/19758234/5456016" target = "_blank">here</a>. What we're going to do is use information contained in this post, use the solutions, and make it look nice. Let's copy the code below into our <code>application.scss</code> (Note that the footer height is changed to be <code>120px</code> instead of <code>60px</code> as it is shown in the StackOverflow post).
</p>

<pre><code class="css">
/* Styles go here */

/* Sticky footer styles
-------------------------------------------------- */

html,
body {
  height: 100%;
  /* The html and body elements cannot have any padding or margin. */
}

/* Wrapper for page content to push down footer */
#wrap {
  min-height: 100%;
  height: auto;
  /* Negative indent footer by its height */
  margin: 0 auto -120px;
  /* Pad bottom by footer height */
  padding: 0 0 120px;
}

/* Set the fixed height of the footer here */
#footer {
  height: 120px;
  background-color: #f5f5f5;
}
</code></pre>

<p>
  Then what we're going to do is wrap all of our content in a div with an <code>id</code> of <code>wrap</code>. So right before the code for the navbar begins (right after the opening <code>body</code> tag and right before the opening nav), let's add <code>&lt;div id = "wrap"&gt;</code> and close the <code>div</code> right before the closing <code>body</code> tag.
</p>

<p>
  Right after the closing <code>div</code> that we just inserted, let's steal the footer code from the StackOverflow post above and paste it into our code. It should look something like this.
</p>

<pre><code class="erb">
&lt;!--closing div for div id = "wrap"--&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div id="footer"&gt;
  &lt;div class="container"&gt;
    
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre>

<p>
	Make sure to put the footer code right before the closing <code>body</code> tag and also right after the closing div tag for the <code>&lt;div id = "wrap"&gt;</code>.
</p>

<p>
  Awesome! Now that we've set up our footer to stick to the bottom of the page, let's start adding in some content into it.
</p>

<p>
  According to our wireframes, we want to have 3 columns inside our footer. Using the <strong>bootstrap grid system</strong>, let's implement this.
</p>

<p>
  Before we do this though, we should also think about what we want the site to look like on mobile screens before thinking about what it should look like on the desktop screen. This is called a <strong>mobile-first approach</strong>.
</p>

<p>
  On mobile phones, instead of trying to displaying 3 columns in one row on a tiny smartphone screen, it would probably be better to display 1 column in each row.
</p>

<p>
  So on mobile phones, the content should display a new row for each column, and on larger screens, it should display 3 columns all in one row.
</p>

<p>
  We can do this by adding a <code>&lt;div class = "col-xs-12 col-md-4"&gt;</code>. What this is saying is this: On a super small screen, use the full width of 12 in the row, and on a medium screen or larger, use 4 (out of 12 in each row). For a refresher on the bootstrap grid system, revisit this lesson <a href="/html_css/9" target="_blank">here</a>.
</p>

<p>
	Let's duplicate this and make 2 more of these <code>div</code>s in the footer to make 3 seperate columns in one row on a medium screen. Let's also remember not to forget to wrap it in a <code>row</code>. So now it should look something like this.
</p>

<pre><code class="erb">
&lt;!--closing div for div id = "wrap"--&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div id="footer"&gt;
  &lt;div class="container"&gt;
    &lt;div class = "row"&gt;
      &lt;div class = "col-xs-12 col-md-4"&gt;
        
      &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class = "col-xs-12 col-md-4"&gt;
        
      &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class = "col-xs-12 col-md-4"&gt;
        
      &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre>

<p>
  Now we can add content inside of here. Feel free to add whatever you want inside of here. This is what I added to my app.
</p>

